<h1>Bucherer-Bergs Reaction</h1>
<p>A 
multi-component reaction between a ketone, potassium cyanide and 
ammonium carbonate, which leads to the formation of hydantoins.</p>
<p><img src="bucher1.gif" width="283" height="78"></p>
<p>A 
pre-formed cyanohydrin can react with ammonium carbonate to give the 
same product:</p>
<p><img src="bucher2.gif" width="281" height="79"></p>
<hr>
<h2>Mechanism of the Bucherer-Bergs Reaction</h2>
<p><img src="bucher0.gif" width="485" height="55"></p>
<p><img src="bucher4.gif" width="456" height="209"></p>
<p>The Bucherer-Bergs Reaction is equivalent to the <a href="strecker-synthesis.shtm">Strecker Synthesis</a>  with &quot;additional CO<sub>2</sub>&quot;. Hydantoins may be 
opened to yield
<i>N</i>-carbamoylamino acids which form amino acids by treatment with acid or 
with a suitable enzyme:</p>
<p><img src="bucher3.gif" width="310" height="96">
</p>
<div style="margin: 15 0 5 -7; padding: 7 4 7 4; border: 1px solid #DDDDDD; clear:both">
